  "diary": "Started the shift early this morning—coffee tasted better than usual, maybe because the sun was already bright over Madrona by the time I left. The commute downtown was smooth, no traffic to fight. At the station, we caught the USA-Wales match on the break room TV around 11. The crew got into it, a lot of good-natured trash talk. I grabbed a bagel from that spot near Molly Moon's during lunch; the whole downtown felt alive with the World Cup energy, bars opening early everywhere. Afternoon was routine—couple of maintenance calls, nothing major. We grilled some chicken for dinner out back, took advantage of that perfect 74-degree evening. The city looked clean and golden as I headed home. Nights like this remind me why I love this job.",
  "thought_process": "The World Cup timing actually shifted my mood—usually Mondays feel heavy, but there was this collective buzz downtown that was infectious. I chose to stay present with the crew during the match instead of ducking into paperwork; after 20-plus years, I know these moments matter more than I initially think. The Light Rail closure didn't affect my commute route, which was lucky. Watching the team play with that kind of focus and heart made me reflect on my own job—there's something about working in service alongside other people that feels right. The beautiful weather helped too. I wasn't exhausted at day's end, just satisfied and ready to rest.",
